4.52/5  rDev +0.9%look: 4.75 | smell: 4.5 | taste: 4.5 | feel: 4.5 |  overall: 4.52014 Vintage
A: 4.75 Looks nice and thick on the pour. Pitch black with a two-inch tan head that lasts a few minutes.
S: 4.5 The aromas are very impressive. The description of what goes into the beer seemed a bit over the top, however, most of the characteristics seem present. There’s a good amount of roasted malt, coffee, and bittersweet chocolate at first followed by raspberry and vanilla. The berry aromas add a nice brightness that balances out the richer, darker elements. A very subtle earthiness is also present which goes nicely with the fairly mild oak.
T: 4.5 Similar to the nose, just a bit less subtle. The same roasty coffee and chocolate flavors come through first, but the subsequent berry flavors are much more dominant than on the nose. The wine barrels add at lot more than expected; there’s some bitterness which is probably coming primarily from the malt, but it seems like some is also coming from the wine as there is an almost tannic quality. Cinnamon and vanilla mix well with the molasses and the very light licorice flavor. The finish is fairly bitter, complimenting the fruity sweetness at the beginning.
M: 4.5 The mouthfeel is nearly perfect; very thick with a great carbonation level. The finish is a tiny bit too dry, but that’s an extremely minor detail.
O: 4.5 I’ve been wanting to try this beer for nearly four years now and was very excited to finally have the opportunity. I really didn’t know what to expect and was presently surprised. It is unlike any other barrel aged stout I’ve had; not at all similar to something like BCBS. Rather, the additives and, perhaps more importantly, the wine barrel a great fruitiness to counter the dark, rich beer. Glad to finally have this and was not let down. 1,755 charactersTele, Dec 06, 2014
3.88/5  rDev -13.4%look: 4.5 | smell: 4 | taste: 4 | feel: 3 |  overall: 3.75In the glass, yea it's dark... living up to it's name. Aroma gives off licorice, coffee/espresso, molasses, wine and chocolate flavors. The actual taste really only follows through with the licorice, bitter chocolate and espresso-coffee booziness. There is a slight wine and cherry tartness coming through, which I'm not a huge fan of, but it's not overpowering. 
While tasty, the problem for me is that no single flavor really shines through. All the flavors got lost in The Abyss? The overall flavor profile seems somewhat unbalanced and a little bit messy. Several sips in, it gets a bit one-note with the roasty booziness. 
Many people have said this is great with a year or more on it, and it might be... but any truly great beer should get BETTER with age, but still be excellent fresh as well.  Very good, but not great... and overall, not worth the $17.99 per bomber price-tag. 
I think it would be amazing for Deschutes to do a 100% bourbon barrel-aged version, but they seem to be against 100% barrel aging for whatever reason.
*Edit... having a 2014 on 12/2/2016, two years later and the review from 2 years ago is still true. Didn't get any better with age and it just still taste like a non-barrel aged massively roasty stout with a somewhat acrid mouthfeel with very little barrel character. Although the 2015 vintage did taste a bit better even fresh. 1,370 charactersmig100, Dec 06, 2014
