4.47/5  rDev -0.2%look: 4.5 | smell: 4.25 | taste: 4.5 | feel: 4.75 |  overall: 4.5A- Pours thick and syrupy as any beer that I have seen. Pure black in the glass with a one finger head. The head is thick and creamy in texture and chocolatey in color. Lacing is tremendous due to the thickness of the head.
S- Huge dark and burnt malts hit the nose right up front. Sweet and dark licorice and chocolate scents follow up the dark malts. Towards the end of the smell the licorice sweetness really ramps up and is the dominant lingering scent. 
T- Starts off with a bang of dark malts that are primarily burnt in flavor. The licorice is prominent behind the malts, providing a dark sweetness. Just a touch of barrel character is detectable underneath all of the aforementioned flavors. Just the slightest touch of red wine fruitiness is detectable before the malts take over again and give you the lingering flavor.
M- Thick and smooth as hell on the whole. Very low carbonation and an alcohol content that is largely hidden by the dark malts.
Overall a wonderfully dark and complex beer. Smooth and easy drinking as imperial stouts come, this one could really sneak up on you, but it is totally worth it. 1,123 charactersboilermakerbrew, Sep 28, 2014
