A: pours a beautiful, jet black with an excellent fingers worth of thick, tan head which leaves good lacing and nice retention. A fair amount lingers around the edges and in the center of the glass.
S: roasted malts, vanilla, some oak, a bit of alcohol strength, nice dark chocolates.
T: up front lots of roasted malts, this is followed by, what I think is licorice? maybe the cherry bark? I get some vanilla from the wood, and some oak. lots of flavors in play here. Alcohol strength is hidden fairly well, though I feel its warming effects in my stomach. As the beer warms the licorice fades and the bourbon and wine barrel qualities start to show themselves, however, every so slightly. Do not taste much if any of the flavors of the barrel initially (only that oak and vanilla.) 
