3.96/5  rDev -11.6%look: 5 | smell: 4 | taste: 3.75 | feel: 4.5 |  overall: 3.75650ml bottle, 2012 vintage, best before 11/1/2013, close enough for me, poured into a Deschutes Teku glass.
The beer pours a deep jet black color, very opaque, hues of cola brown at the edges when struck by the light. Atop the beer rests a nice, fluffy, caramel colored head that sits about 2 fingers high that has very good retention and leaves a large network of soapy lace behind. The aroma is pleasant, bakers chocolate, lightly roasted coffee, molasses, stone fruit and red wine, some charred oak, smooth yet potent alcohol brings out some bourbon and toffee sweetness. It's busy, not quite balanced, but complex and interesting. The flavors are a bit harsher, lots of roasted malt, burnt wood, toasted coffee bean, it doesn't breach the smoked threshold, but is one of the roastiest beers I've tasted. Behind that, some nice layers of stone fruit, red wine bring out some molasses and brown sugar before bourbon, chocolate and alcohol wash over the finish. It's complex, but way out of balance, perhaps too young. The mouthfeel is nice, low carbonation but still lively, rich texture coats the mouth well before finishing easily, a little pricklier than I'd like but nice and creamy. 
Verdict: Too young? Hard to say, but the roast quality is very taxing. The complexity is rewarding, but the balance is less than admirable. I'd like to visit some older vintages with more time on them to see how this beer evolves, but for a beer that is nearly a year old, it's a bit of a shame that it's this undeveloped. 1,515 characterskevanb, Oct 15, 2013
