4.97/5  rDev +10.9%look: 4.5 | smell: 5 | taste: 5 | feel: 5 |  overall: 5Blind review, blind bif 7.
 Buzz picks beers 3a. & 3b. Shared with two non-b.a. friends earlier today. Here are the notes.
 3a: Pours opaque, black as night. 1/8" dark caramel colored head, falls to a ring, no lacing.(4.5)
 I was expecting a blast of bourbon, instead I find a wonderfully balanced aroma. Hints of dark chocolate, coco, raisinets, espresso, hints of horehound, vanilla, and toasted marshmallow.(5.0)
 Flavors follows the nose, bitter-sweet chocolate being the dominate flavor, espresso, toasted marshmallow, caramel...its complex, and perfectly balanced.(5.0)
 Full bodied, slightly carbonated, somewhere between dry, and creamy. Easy to drink for a heavy beer.(5.0)
 This, I believe is the best beer that Ive ever had; my tasting partners are digging it as well. It is a perfectly balanced Imp. Stout.(5.0)
3b: Pours opaque, the color of spent motor oil. 1/2" caramel colored head falls to a ring.(4.5)
 This one has some of that bourbon that I was expecting, but not overwhelmingly so...peaty, dark chocolate, espresso, root-beer, and vanilla. Nicely balanced as well.(4.5)
 Flavors follow the nose...bitter-sweet chocolate, & bourbon up front with toasted marshmallow, & root-beer in the middle, with a bitter-sweet finish.(5.0)
 Full bodied, slightly bitter, drier than the other, but still has a slight creaminess. A huge beer that is easy to sip.(4.5)
 Another great beer. Barrel aging is evident, but not overwhelmingly so. Balanced, and easy to drink...a wonderful beer to share amongst friends.(4.5)
 Holy hell we have climbed out of The Abyss...3a was 2007 vintage, 3b was 2010 vintage. Thats so f*#king huge! Never would have guessed that 3a was aged that long, it held up so well to being in the bottle that long, absolutely no oxidation.
 Thank you so much slaphappysnark, and stupac2 for sending this huge want. 1,856 characterssitarist, Oct 29, 2012
