5/5  rDev +11.6%jrkoller, Aug 22, 2012
4.38/5  rDev -2.2%look: 4.5 | smell: 4 | taste: 4.5 | feel: 4.5 |  overall: 4.5We pop our bottle of 2010 stock and pour a jet black brew. It holds a brief one finger head of dark brown bubbles. This recedes rather quickly, leaving a ring of bubbles around the glass’ edges, and a ghostly film across the top of the liquid. Swirls slosh patterned, spotty lacing around the glass, and produce an even bigger, better retaining head than the original pour. The brew appears syrupy, and the lighter looking carbonation rises slowly. No sediment is noted. The aroma is heavy with dark chocolate malts and molasses. The former show a thick metallic sheen, and a soy sauce saltiness. The bourbon barreling becomes apparent only with warmth, but when it does it stings the nostrils with burning fumes. Buttery diacetyls and light vanilla help to add spice, while cooling the aroma a bit. Our first impression is that there is such a deep char and smoke to this, while it stays very sweet with syrupy chocolates. As we sip, sugary sweet melted chocolate nibs, mixing with metallic, chocolate malts start things off. The bourbon flavoring is there, but quickly mixes with the deepest, smokiest burnt malts, which reduces its prominence. The peak is sweet, with cooked brown sugar, warm molasses, black pepper, buttery bourbon, and general fusel booziness. These all mix, pushing to a finish that is smoother, with rich melted chocolate, clean chocolate and caramel malts. It is actually quite sweet and incredibly smooth until an insane char, smoke, booze, and a curious hot pepper spiciness rumble up from the last drops left in the mouth. The aftertaste breathes of fusel booze, thick char, smoked ham, raw cocoa, and raw coffee bean. The body is thick as mud, and the carbonation is light to medium. Each sip affords nice, sticky slurp and pop, with a slick coating all over the lips and palate. The booziness helps to scorch and dry the mouth, leaving it slightly astringent with the raw chocolatiness of it all. The abv is strong and the beer catches up with you, but it drinks nicely. You just don’t want to see it go, so you certainly sit back and let it set its own pace.
Overall, what we enjoyed most about this brew was the flavoring. The char is outrageous!! This aspect really sets up for a unique malt base for the buttery, toasty bourbon, and the wildly sweet raw and milk chocolates. These all mix for a completely new flavoring that is so complex and gorgeous. The mouthfeel is sticky and inviting, giving you just one more reason to go in for another sip. We were looking high and low for the licorice throughout, but we were never able to pin it down in the nose, and only mildly on the back of the flavoring with black pepper and booze. Regardless, this is a dark, gritty, bold beer that everyone should try at least once. 2,756 charactersTheBrewo, Aug 22, 2012
