A: A pitch black pour with a nice dense medium brown head. Fades very slowly, leaving an almost solid wall of lacing behind. 
S: Hearty roasted malt with some dark chocolate and coffee beans. A bit oaky with some anise and molasses. Creamy.
T: Up front there is oaky vanilla, toffee and molasses along with a boat load of roasted malt. Bitter char with some creamy chocolate and coffee mixed with quite a bit of anise, especially as it warms up. Tons of lingering bitter coffee, chocolate, anise and a little smoke in the aftertaste. Flavors are sharp and just a touch boozy.
M: Heavy. Fairly thick but not syrupy. 
O: Deceptively big imperial stout. I've had weaker beers that feel like they're twice as strong. Flavors are complex, varied and well balanced. Flavors stand out and are quite sharp as previously noted. Overall a great stout, up there with some of the best. With some more age and some mellowing it could become incredible. The label DOES state, best AFTER 8/12. 1,020 charactersDope, May 07, 2012
