Very light carbonation -- almost no head on pouring, but the sparkle is there on sipping. I could go on and on about the wonderful aroma and big molasses and chocolate flavor, but I'll focus instead on that mouthfeel. For me, it doesn't get better than a big strong stout with serious body but a truly refreshing feel. "Thin" is usually a pejorative, but this had no hint of the stickiness found in a young version of the same or Stoic -- it just flows in a really magical way. Very impressed -- it's drinking fantastically right now and I truffle to imagine improvement with age. Open now! 632 charactersdrgarage, Dec 04, 2011
4.62/5  rDev +3.1%look: 4.5 | smell: 5 | taste: 4.5 | feel: 4.5 |  overall: 4.5This is a review for the 2009.
Finally opened by last 2009 today, which I will be following up with one of my 2010s and a new 2011 (I'm splitting bottles - I can't imagine drinking that much on my own, ha).
A - Pretty carbonated still coming out of the bottle. Slightly paler head than the last newer vintage I had, but still looking like glorious used motor oil.
S - Smells like gingerbread drowned in molasses.
T - Blackstrap molasses, leather, and ginger. Lingering aftertaste. My last sip was 1 minute ago and I'm still tasting the ginger. Well-rounded, though, with an established mid-palate.
M - Heavy but smooth.
D - It's more mellow than the newer bottles, so it's pretty drinkable. Still a very, very strong stout, but not quite as sticky on the palate as the 2010 was earlier this year when I drank it.
Definitely worth waiting to open my last bottle. This beer has really evolved since its release. 916 charactersjekka, Dec 04, 2011
