4.62/5  rDev +3.1%look: 4.5 | smell: 5 | taste: 4.5 | feel: 4.5 |  overall: 4.5Had this 2010 bottle at a stout night with friends. It was Ivan, Abyss, Darkness, and Dark Lord, in that order. We had pretzels and water and some Goose Island Summertime in between rounds.
This pours deep black with a little half finger espresso crema head leaving a little lace as it dies. On the nose there is rich espresso, cacao nibs, deeply roasted malt, and slight bourbon undertones. This is a great nose, totally different than the other three beers that night. In the mouth the espresso and chocolate are perfectly in balance. It seemed a bit less sweet than the others, probably due to a lack of the heavy molasses notes that dominate the others, or perhaps due to a more pronounced coffee bitterness counteracting the sweeter flavors. There might be some hop-type bitterness too. It's a really rich taste that I'm going to have to spend more time with to really understand it. The body is full with a long finish, slightly warming from the bourbon and general alcohol content, with the bitter and sweeter notes mixing together very well for quite some time.
Overall, this is a very fine stout, one of the better ones I've had. It was by far the most unique one of the four that we had, and I guess now I see why this is classed as an American big stout rather than a Russian Imperial. Great beer.
EDIT - I just drank my first 2011 bottle, and it's amazing fresh. The smell is unreal.
EDIT 2 - I've been frequenting my local place, where they've got 2010 Abyss on tap for $5 a pint. Very fine at a year old. I could almost just smell the beer. 1,558 charactersEricCioe, Jul 10, 2011
