4.67/5  rDev +4.2%look: 4.5 | smell: 5 | taste: 4.5 | feel: 5 |  overall: 4.5Poured into a tulip from a 22oz nicely waxed bottle.
Vintage: 2010 Reserve
The inside of the cap says "Bravely Done".
A - Pours a near ink blot dark brown with a nice tan head that was about .5 inches and receded fairly quickly. It didn't seem as viscous as other Stouts of this caliber. The head has some nice tight bubbles that stick around after a nice swirl. 
S - Aroma is delicious in this beer. Molasses, sweet caramel, nice raisin notes with some slight bready and oat notes. Good grain backbone on a strong beer. Slight roasted espresso notes as well as some mild dark chocolate and some sweet milk chocolate. There is some great woody and oak notes on the finish as well. Some boozy sweetness is also perceived. The licorice is slightly perceived but it doesn't dominate at all. 
T & M - Not as viscous as expected. Starts off with some roasted coffee notes and some nice molasses sweetness. The licorice can be perceived a bit more on the palette. Good dark fruit sweetness as well. There is some nice bourbon notes and alcohol burn that balances out some of the roasted notes. There is very slight chocolate notes that seem to be downplayed by the boozy aspect. It is quite light for a double Stout and I attribute that to the barrel aging. There are some slight woody dry notes on the back end as well. Pretty well balanced stout with a good mix of roast, bourbon notes and molasses sweetness. The body is nice and full with great complexity. Solid offering and I can see why its so hyped.
D - It is delicious but it could be hard to drink more than one based on flavor intensity and ABV. Still great offer. 1,624 charactersJoEBoBpr, Mar 10, 2011
