4.72/5  rDev +5.4%look: 4.5 | smell: 5 | taste: 5 | feel: 4.5 |  overall: 4This is the 2010 vintage. Poured from the bomber into a Trappist chalice.
A: True to its name - absolutely black with not a speck of light shining through. Head is almost nonexistent - half a finger of brown foam that dissipates in under a minute. 
S: This is one of those beers you can smell from several feet away, and actually you can make out several different notes from a distance. Your olfactory glands explode when the beer is brought up close. Roasted malt and black coffee at first, then a bit of vanilla and a hint of anise and brown sugar. Mocha and progressively sweeter chocolate notes come into play, and there is a creamy flash there at the end before a woody and roasted character takes over everything again.
T: So so rich, at first bitter chocolate and some woody character with a bit of anise. Char and some smoke. Then milk chocolate and a hint of cream. Spices. Tobacco. Finishes bittersweet with a mocha character. W bit of a whisky finish in there as well. Very strong - dominates the palate and floods the senses. Excellent.
M: Super smooth and masks alcohol extremely well. Slight dryness toward the end, but leaves you wanting more.
D: Rich rich rich. Got through the bottle but need a big break afterwards. A slow sipper for sure, but I could see myself coming back to this again and again.
I want to see this with a bit of age on it. A top stout even without age. Excellent beer. 1,414 charactersBucBasil, Mar 06, 2011
