4.15/5  rDev -7.4%look: 4 | smell: 4 | taste: 4 | feel: 4.5 |  overall: 4.52007 vintage (consumed on 2/9/11):
A huge thanks to ThreeWiseMen for sharing this with JustinA1 and myself. Poured into a snifter.
Pours out pitch black, perhaps the blackest stout I have seen. A small dark tan head emerges and swirling gives the head a nice foamy texture. Allowing the beer to settle the head recedes to a ring around the glass. Absolutely no light is getting though the body of this even if you held it up next to a light. A very nice looking RIS.
Huge roast is the first thing to greet the nose. Followed up by molasses and some other sweetness (perhaps some chocolate?). No licorice is present but that could be because of the age of the bottle. Slight charred notes emerges as the beer warms.
Much like the smell, roast and molasses are the most noticeable elements in the taste. The sweetness from the molasses lingers in the taste well after the beer is swallowed. Scorched sugars presents itself as times goes on. A bitterness is also found in the finish and a hint of smokiness. This is a very unique tasting beer and the three of us agreed we hadn't had anything like it before.
A bit light for a RIS but perhaps that's due to the age (no idea if aging can really thin a beer, going to have to open a 2010 to see if there is a difference). It's not that it's thin, it's just light, like mousse. The liquid is very smooth and it goes down incredibly well. I want to give this a 4.25. (Gave this a 4.5 to end up with the A- range I was looking for)
This was a very unique taste experience for sure. I think that the 07s are holding up very well. The flavor profile is very nice but yet subtle and have to sort of dig for some flavors at first. I don't know how much longer this would have continued to age and get better. If you have an 07 you will no be disappointed if you open it up now. 1,820 charactersSwimsum, Feb 22, 2011
