2015 review:
Pours black with some dark brown on the edges. If poured aggressively the head can be enormous.  I always find it funny when people say how many fingers of head they got when they pour like its any reliable indicature because it's all relative to the glass, the temperature of the beer, and how you pour the beer. Anyways. The head sticks around for a little bit but it's a big beer so expected. 
Smells include burnt malt, brown sugar, earthy hops, slight barrel but hard to distinguish, some booze (perhaps a little too fresh), slight dark fruit like a fig. I see this one is aged 50 percent in barrels as opposed to other recent variations which were more around 30. Interestingly I don't get any more barrel character. It is a pretty bitter beer at this point. The roasted character is making this a dry bitter supper with an underlying sweetness.
Mouth feel is smooth and medium to full.
I always love this beer aged and I think that this one will be no exception. I can see the heat dying down a little bit the dark fruits and some of the barrel coming through a little bit more over time. Right now I have to say this beer is very good, but after some time I could see it being a world class beer. 2,133 charactersmellowmark, Jan 01, 2011
4.46/5  rDev -0.4%look: 4.5 | smell: 3.5 | taste: 5 | feel: 4.5 |  overall: 4.5One of the beers included in the 2010 Christmas tasting with my brother (Mississipping) and our dad. Poured from a 2009 bottle--thankfully not infected--into a Bruery snifter.
Appearance:
Black as night. Head was a carmel tan/brown. Originally about one finger think that slowly dissipated into a thing ring with large bubble clusters. 
Smell:
Very strong bourbon scent with hints of caramel and chocolate. There was also a strong smoke smell, but overall not very dynamic and a little disappointing.
Taste:
Not disappointing at all! Bourbon hits the palat first and is quickly followed by a smoky flavor. As it lingers in your mouth and hits the back of your throat the taste changes dramatically. First you begin to notice a chocolate flavor that is bold and stays with you for a long time. Then you begin to notice a licorice flavor and is finished by a toffee flavor that lingers for minutes. As it warms there is a strong coffee flavor that begins to show up more and more. It is very hidden at first, but will almost become overpowering if warm. The alcohol is very well masked and almost unnoticeable. 
Mouthfeel:
Full-bodied. Very smooth and lingers for hours. Not too thick, but coats the whole mouth which allows you to notice the changing of all the flavors. Very drying at the end.
Drinkability:
A very slow drinker and definitely a sipper. Our bottle, split 3 ways, lasted between 45 minutes and an hour. The flavors keep you coming back for more and also make you want to take your time to enjoy the complexity of the beer. 1,547 charactersStayWhatYouAre2, Dec 31, 2010
