4.51/5  rDev +0.7%look: 5 | smell: 4 | taste: 5 | feel: 4.5 |  overall: 42009 vintage, poured at just under 50 degrees into a laser-etched 0,4l snifter.
Appearance - Don't bother trying to look through it, as it is opaque; one of the darkest beers around, it's as black as hole in space. Thick mocha head full of suds, with excellent retention and moderate lace.
Smell - Malt and yeast up front, followed by coffee and chocolate. A little bit of molasses follows, though faint. A little bit of oakiness comes out as the beer opens up. The smell was very potent right as the bottle was opened.
Taste - Incredibly full-bodied, this brew tastes like a beer latte. The coffee and chocolate character apparent in the aroma blend in the beer to give the malty character an almost mocha taste. Grain is subtle. Malt is a little roasted and a little sweet. Overall, the beer is incredibly balanced. Hop character is spicy, with bitterness building after a while. Very little noticeable alcohol heat.
Mouthfeel - Creamy foaminess, heavy on the tongue, lighter going down. Thick as it is, the beer is remarkably viscous. Carbonation isn't huge, but makes itself known. All aspects of the mouthfeel only serve to compliment the taste.
Drinkability - This one went by too quickly. For as heavy a beer as it is, you shouldn't be able to drink it this quickly. For the style, the drinkability is remarkable.
Overall - I wouldn't mind having a few more bottles of this business. There's no question that it's a truly world-class beer. If you can get your hands on it, don't hesitate.
NB - Drank a bottle of this in May of 2010, and another in December 2010, both 2009 vintage. The one with less age was more sweet with hotter booziness; the one with more age was more balanced, drier, and the alcohol was much less noticeable. This review is based on the December tasting. 1,791 charactersChronofied, Dec 24, 2010
4/5  rDev -10.7%look: 4 | smell: 4 | taste: 4 | feel: 4 |  overall: 4Doing a comparison of 09 and 10. With my buddy Pete who's in town for the holidays. Welcome home Pete. Both poured into the same St. Bernardus snifter with a thorough rinsing between each.
09:
Note: I have had several 09 Abyss bottles this year and have yet to have an infected one. This one is no different. The case I bought must have been from a better batch. Thank the stars.
A: Color is a brown stained black. With nice quarter finger head and simple lacing. Mild retention.
S: A wide variety of flavors come out. A smokey alcohol sent up front, cocoa, tobacco, some woody barrel hints. 
T: Pretty much as it smells, but much less boozy than I would have thought given the smokey alcohol aroma. The cocoa really shines here. Hints of toffee and tobacco as well. Definitely recommend letting it warm up as the flavors really come out.
M: Rich and thick, smooth viscous texture. Slight bubbling.
D: After a year of aging the alcohol is well hidden. Very tasty and smooth. Very easy to drink. Surprisingly so for such a big stout.
Overall: I love it. I'm excited to see to see how it continues to change as I still have a few and have had great luck with them. I still prefer Parabola, but to date this continues to be one of the best Imp Stouts I've ever had. Deserving of all the praise it receives.
Now on to the 2010 batch to conclude my little comparison.
2010:
Note: Under the cap, which was difficult to remove because it's wax sealed, are printed the words "Bravely Done". I thought this was a subtle but nice touch.
A: Slightly darker than the 09. The brownish tint is not present as it was in the 09. Very little to no head, less than seen in the 09.
S: Wow. Much less bourbon to the aroma. Cocoa is much more dominant than in the 09. Hints of coffee and vanilla. A very nutty presence that has taken me by surprise.
T: I have to say wow again. Strong cocoa flavor. With a nutty presence. Again, much less smokey alcohol presence than the 09 but still present. Chocolate maltyness. Quite delicious.
M: Slightly more viscous than the 09, but the reduced carbonation makes this softer on the tongue. Very smooth.
D: Due to the reduced carbonation and the great job they did hiding the alcohol, this is incredibly drinkable. Especially for such a heavy stout.
Overall: I find this to be superior fresh than the 09 was with a year on it. Fantastic. I will enjoy drinking this batch for years to come and look forward to seeing how it ages. Well done Deschutes. I highly recommend this to anyone and everyone.
My score for 09 is:
A: 3.5, S: 3.5, T: 4.0, M: 4.0, D: 3.0 = B
My score for 10 is:
A: 4.0, S: 4.0, T: 4.0, M: 4.0, D: 4.0 = A 2,649 charactersmrmiles, Dec 24, 2010
3.4/5  rDev -24.1%look: 4 | smell: 4 | taste: 3 | feel: 4 |  overall: 3This review is for the 2010 batch.
Pours pitch black with a big, tan, finely laced head. Head slowly progresses to lingering rocky tan head. Very beautiful.
Aroma was very nice and filled with big wafts of caramel and molasses.
Flavor was huge right off the bat. Over the top with licorice and molasses, followed with more moderate caramel. Alcohol is beyond warming, seems a bit hot. Can taste some of the bourbon barrel up front, but quickly is overpowered by the other flavors. Bitterness is herbal and quite apparent.
Mouthfeel is creamy and lingers down the throat. Very nice.
Overall this beer had some interesting flavors that I felt were not well balanced. The licorice and molasses combined with the hop bitterness did not meld well for my pallet. There was not enough oak flavor for me. Some reviewers have said that they prefer this low oakiness to other over-oaked stouts, but for me it was too subtle, or perhaps just overpowered by the licorice, molasses and hop flavors. I wish it would have had more time in the barrel or a higher proportion of barrel aged beer in the blend. This said, I would like to save a bottle in the cellar for 1-3 years to see if the flavors become more harmonious with age. 1,220 characterslionchow, Dec 23, 2010
4.25/5  rDev -5.1%look: 4.5 | smell: 4.5 | taste: 4 | feel: 5 |  overall: 4Pours a deep, dark brown colour, very dark with just a murky brown at the rim. Head is a deep, dark umber - possibly the darkest head I've seen. Sinking here and there but retains a wonderful, really impressive thick amount. Lace is very impressive and clumpy and just hangs around. That beer is here to stay. Very impressive.
Smells very rich and roasty, but not burnt. Has a strong unsweetened chocolate component, sweet at the back but mostly just intense toastiness. Pleasant spice along with it, some cumin, star anise and nutmeg. Slight sour woody note as well; very pleasant indeed.
Taste is really quite intense. A lot of dry roasted characters with potent cocoa and leather on the front as well as dark roasted grain. As with all very good imperial stouts, one sip explodes with flavour in my mouth, foregoing the need to drink this too quickly without savouring. There's a really strong alcohol heat from quite early in the palate, which is complemented by harsh spice, pepper and aniseed. Fortunately there is no fusel alcohol flavour and it's just warm and a delightful stinging giving me exquisite pain. Some fruit on the back, with figs and oak wood and a slight smokey edge. Very explosive, flavoursome and complex beer. However, I can't say I'm as enamoured with this as I have been with others in the same vein - Avery Mephistopheles remains the yardstick to me.
Perfectly weighted body, heavy but smooth with a Midash touch as it glissandoes down. Marvelous.
Yeah, that hot alcohol is a downer. But don't let that put a dampener on this otherwise damn fine gargantuan beer. 1,595 characterslaituegonflable, Dec 23, 2010
