3.81/5  rDev -15%look: 4.5 | smell: 3.5 | taste: 4 | feel: 3 |  overall: 4Review #400. 2009 Bomber, courtesy of Somabeer, served at cellar temp. Don't be infected, don't be infected, no whammies, no whammies, stop!
A: Uh oh. This is definitely on the high end of carbonation for a stout, with the tulip winding up split halfway between fully black liquid and creamy, frothy brown foam. Pretty good retention and nice chunky lacing make this a great looking beer, even if the prevalence of carbonation makes me worry about bugs.
S: Well, it isn't a total sour mess, but I'm definitely getting some off notes (from what I expected). I'm getting lots of licorice up front, as well as bourbon and oak. Some fruitiness is there, but unfortunately it's more tart cherry than candied fig. It's weird - some inhalations yield lovely notes of chocolate, malt, vanilla, and licorice, while others are vinous, tannic, astringent, and tart. Man, this must be an amazing beer when it isn't slightly infected. Even so, it varies between great and mediocre, but is never bad.
T: Opens with sweet chocolatey malt, molasses, licorice, coffee, and bourbon - all amazing. The finish, though, brings the off flavors promised by the nose: red wine, tannin, and cherry. While the wine lover in me appreciates the vinous qualities of this beer, I really don't think that this is quite what The Abyss is supposed to taste like. Again, I can only imagine how good it must be when uninfected, since I'm really enjoying it as is.
M: The explosion of carbonation from the initial (soft) pour seems to have stripped the beer itself of all its life. At least it still has a nice full body, but without any effervescence to help clean things up. It gets pretty darn sticky.
D: Part of me is loving drinking this beer, since there are just so many variables in its flavor and aroma profiles - if complexity alone is a virtue, then this beer definitely deserves high praise. Some sips seems perfectly stout-y, and then others are overbearingly astringent. One thing worth noting is that alcohol is remarkably absent from the picture, almost unbelievably so for an 11% beer. It is doing a great job of warming me up on a cool day, though.
Notes: I don't really know how I feel about this one - while I'm obviously disappointed that my first experience with this legendary beer was less than transcendent, I'm still having a great time exploring its complexities - even the unintended ones. I do hope that my other bottle of 2009 is pristine, but my heart isn't broken to have gotten a bottle that's slightly off. Now if I can just convince Hopstoopid120 to include me in the party when he does his full Abyss vertical...
Cheers! 2,627 characterswoosterbill, Sep 12, 2010
