3.61/5  rDev -19.4%look: 4.5 | smell: 3.5 | taste: 3.5 | feel: 3 |  overall: 4The infamous 2009. Unfortunately, I don't have any prior Abyss experience, so I'll just have to compare against what I think it should taste like. 
Pours a deep black, good frothy crema-type head with a lot of staying power. 
Hmmm. In the aroma, there is a *little* tart cherry/grape. I get the typical chocolate, coffee roast aroma too. Depending on the whiff, it's like it's 2 different beers. 
Taste-wise, the slight infection seems to make this a schizophrenic beer. At first, tasted at a fairly cool temperature, I don't find much evidence of infection at all - there's a lot of roasted coffee, charry-type flavors with an undercurrent of licorice. As it warmed a bit, then I started tasting some bitter crushed aspirin flavors that I felt were way out of place in this beer. Then as it warmed further, licorice and roast returned, along with a little tart cherry at the back end. It is complex, no doubt about that...but it does seem to be showing some signs of infection. 
It's the mouthfeel where the bugs are most apparent, IMO. Again, while I don't have experience with prior year bottles of Abyss, I'm pretty sure it's supposed to be somewhat thicker and less light/effervescent. It did not have big-beer feel - the body was closer to that of a Jolly Pumpkin-esque wild ale. Maybe I'm exaggerating it a bit, it's not quite *that* light yet, but it seems to be heading in that direction. I'm fairly sure this beer isn't supposed to be like that. 
The lightened body and dry finish probably help make this easier to drink, to an extent. In any event, the beer isn't so badly infected yet that you wouldn't be able to drink it. I could see finishing off the bomber without too much trouble. 1,703 charactersPatrick999, Sep 06, 2010
