4.55/5  rDev +1.6%look: 4 | smell: 4 | taste: 5 | feel: 4.5 |  overall: 4.5Another major storm in 2010 left us in the dark here in Arlington. For the snowstorm I opened something special (my first KBS), so for this one I decided to open something special as well. 2008 vintage poured from a 22oz bottle into my Portsmouth tulip. Poured a thick black color with a moderate mocha head filling a half inch of the glass. Decent head retention and lacing overall. 
The aroma shows a good amount of chocolate flavor along with some roasted malts. A little bit of the oak comes through and seems to smooth out the flavors a bit. I get some of the molasses I think but don't seem to get much of the licorice. Very good aroma overall.
The taste starts off with more bitter-sweet chocolate, smooth characteristic to it. By the time the finish comes around more of a bold, roasted, burnt, bitter flavor is present and lingers after the finish. The roasted and bitter flavors definitely smoothed out a bit after it warmed. The licorice and molasses started to come through just a bit as it warmed as well. It shows both sweet and bitter flavors well throughout and they balance each other very nicely. Very smooth overall for the strength and size of this beer. It's tough to not give this a 5 on taste, I'm not sure what else I could ask for in an imperial stout. 
The mouthfeel is definitely one of the thicker imperial stouts I've had, but not quite as thick as Dark Lord. Carbonation is on the lower side which I also like. Great mouthfeel overall for my tastes. Drinkability is very good, it had some fantastic flavors to it and was very well balanced between the sweet chocolaty and the roasted bitterness. Excellent beer overall and an excellent choice to drink by candle light in my dark powerless house. 1,728 charactersbillab914, Aug 06, 2010
