Ignore the scores you see above, I did that to trick the system into giving this bear a 4.6. Screw you beer advocate for giving us the weakest rating system possible.
Went out of my way to go back to Deschutes for the 09' Abyss on tap. Why? Because it's an epic beer.
Appearance: 4.0
I want to give this a higher score but I can't. The head is a nice mocha color perfect for the style. It's black, like darkness sure.. opaque as hell. But the head is wimpy and small, maybe one finger. The lacing is non-existent just like the head retention.
Smell: 4.75
Spot on and bravo. Bourbon, chocolate, wood, and coffe on first impression. Very boozy but in the best kind of way. This is a complex beer, I get dark hints of fruit and molassess and vanilla.
Taste: 4.75
I was initially unimpressed, can you imagine that. Then wisdom sent me caution in the form of a backhand. Why am I drinking this beer so cold. So I waited, and ordered another. When it's cold all you taste is carbonation and a slight burning. When it's warm you get the real deal; liquid heaven. Smoke, wood, and bouron are here hanging out with chocolate and Mr. Coffee Bean. Vanilla is riding on bourbon's shoulders. Ash is over in the corner playing halo. They all greet you like old friends. Do not drink cold or you will be a big fat loser.
Mouthfeel: 4.75
I feel stuck in 4.75 mode. This beer does everything almost as good as perfect, but never quite perfect. It's like in Nascar, you can get second place in every race but win the entire thing in the end. This is a perfect mix of creamy and ashy. Once it warms up the carbonation really really mellows out; truly remarkable 
Drinkability: 4.75
I'm just going to order another one.. only one more I promise. Actually funny story my friends tried to leave and I just snuck back into the place and ordered another one. Then they all did... Good times. 1,923 charactersThreeWiseMen, Jul 25, 2010
4.5/5  rDev +0.4%look: 4.5 | smell: 4.5 | taste: 4.5 | feel: 4.5 |  overall: 4.5Tasting the 2009. 
Pours very dark, with an ample head that dissipates into a fine layer of foam. Leaves lots of clingy lacing. 
Aromas of sour cherries, raisins, chocolate, and coffee. Complex and intriguing. 
There are flavors of dark bitter baker's chocolate, raisins, sour cherries, charred malt, and hops. There is a bit of a sweet and sour thing going on (raisins versus cherries). Tastes just a little pasty in the finish, kind of like chocolate pudding, and then has a long dry hoppy chocolate taste sensation. 
Body is thick and the fine head and carbonation gives it a very creamy mouthfeel. 
This is a huge beer, and very drinkable. I think the '09 version is just a little more sour than previous vintages. I had this at a tasting in April 2010, when it was noticeably more sour than the '08. However, 3 months later, this bottle selected randomly from my cellar collection of 10 bottles, is tasting the same. Whether the extra sourness was intended, I don't know. Sometimes changes occur as a brewery doubles its volume of production. 
I'll try another bottle in 3 mos and see if it has changed, but I think it is not infected, just a slightly more sour version. 1,181 charactersBeerenauslese, Jul 24, 2010
