4.35/5  rDev -2.9%look: 4.5 | smell: 4.5 | taste: 4.5 | feel: 4 |  overall: 4Vintage: 2009, NOT infected!
Appearance -- Pours a deep, rich brown, black in the glass, with a thin tan fog over the liquid line. Extra points for having a constant head, thin as it may be.
Smell -- Mild bourbon and oak, rich dark malt, prune and sweet cherries, faint cocoa and coffee.
Taste -- Not quite as sweet as the nose would suggest: baker's chocolate, raisin and prune, black strap molasses. The bourbon and oak notes are pitch-perfect; they don't overwhelm the base, but accentuate the wonderful flavors therein. The licorice adds a pointed spicy note toward the finish.
Mouthfeel -- Medium to full in body, not as full as I would have liked but it didn't detract from the experience. Carbonation is medium to high in volume and prickly.
Drinkability -- I was planning on letting this sit a while longer, but all of the threads discussing the infection made me get to this one sooner than expected. I don't know if I just happened to get a good bottle, or if the infection is too weak to notice.
Recent quality issues aside, Abyss deserves all of the accolades it has been bestowed. Great depth of flavor, especially with the inclusion of the licorice. The barreling is done with such a delicate touch that it accentuates what's already going on instead of just adding another layer of flavors. Won't risk tracking a new bottle, but I can't wait until the 2010 batch! 1,384 charactersyeahnatenelson, Jul 21, 2010
4.38/5  rDev -2.2%look: 4.5 | smell: 4 | taste: 4.5 | feel: 4.5 |  overall: 4.5Poured from 22oz waxed bomber into a pint glass. This is the '09, so it's labeled as best after November 2010, but I decided to jump the gun a little to celebrate my 500th review. 
Appearance: color is entirely black and allows absolutely no light through. Head is 4 fingers of chunky dark tan foam which leaves a good lace as it dissipates. Wond'rous.
Smell: some chocolate aroma but the biggest things are wood and a slight sourness. I'm not sure whether the latter is intentional or not; it's not necessarily bad, though. Overall, the aroma is good but a little one-dimensional and less complex than I was anticipating.
Taste: flavor parallels well with the aroma in some areas, but is far more complex and dynamic. It starts out a little on the oaky/tart side, then morphs into this big huge malty, somewhat chocolatey and caramelly, but mostly just solid malt flavor, and finishes with a more burnt and roasty characteristic. That tartness and oakiness stays with you though. Damn good.
Mouthfeel: medium-thick body and, while carbonation is relatively low, there's just this fantastic silky-smooth creaminess. I think it's obtained by just great body and texture rather than relying on the carbonation. Love it.
Drinkability: I'm pretty sure this was one of the infected bottles, but really, it could have just as well been a genius recipe. The tartness kind of keeps me wanting more. 
I remember having this on tap when it was fresh last year and having a wholly different experience (of course, that batch was probably not affected by the problems of the bottled '09). I have another bottle cellared so I'm looking forward to trying it again in a year or so to see what's happened to it. 1,701 charactersflagmantho, Jul 21, 2010
4.37/5  rDev -2.5%look: 4 | smell: 4.5 | taste: 4.5 | feel: 4.5 |  overall: 4'09 bottle into Bruery tulip, with another grateful nod to Greg (tpd975). Another fantastic box, Greg!
Pours black, with a nice, robust mocha head that takes awhile to settle into a nice cap. Interesting, somewhat delicate lacing is left as it falls as well. 
Nose is... really interesting. Tart, lactic acid emerging first, followed quickly by clear notes of smooth milk chocolate and black coffee. The acidity is never hidden, but it certainly plays nice with the big, rich, roasty stout qualities, and the end result is interesting and not at all off-putting. Definitely a bit of an Oude Bruin/Imperial Stout hybrid. Those two styles should mate more often. 
Taste is big on the lactic up front, but equally big on smooth, smokey roasted malt and rich chocolate. Acidic lactic bite starts things off, with a big, smokey malt presence emerging quickly after - I wonder if it's the acidity from the lactic pushing the smokeyness I'm getting - and a rich chocolate underpinning bracing the whole affair. Sour cherries make an appearance towards the finish, as the lactic acidity pops it head up just enough to wave goodbye, before riding away on a long, luxurious finish of smokey malt and smooth roastiness. Very, surprisingly, delicious. 
Mouthfeel is a bit on the thin side as a result of this, with a nice bite to the carbonation, but if you'll read my review of Serpent's Stout, you'll know, I kinda dig that sort of thing. Medium bodied, acidity bites the back of the throat on the swallow, and the finish lingers long and beautifully. This is not AT ALL a classic Imperial Stout mouthfeel, but that doesn't stop me from liking it. A lot. 
Drinkability is very nice. A very tasty stout, and the bite from the sourness actually masks any real alcohol notes or bite very well. Impressive once again. 
All in all, I was somewhat expecting the infection, but it's certainly not an unpleasant experience for me at all. If I was rating solidly to style, this would take a bit of a hit, but it still wouldn't be bad - it could certainly pass as a "historical interpretation", as the lactic is certainly not at all overwhelming. However, this isn't a homebrewing competition, so I'm not - I'm rating on how enjoyable I think it is, and I must say, this is pretty intriguing. I really ended up loving this beer. 2,314 charactersJohnQVegas, Jul 21, 2010
