4.72/5  rDev +5.4%look: 4.5 | smell: 5 | taste: 4.5 | feel: 4.5 |  overall: 5Serving type- 2008 Vintage poured into a tulip glass.
A- Pours jet black with a two finger deep tan head that quickly faids to a rather decent lacing. The lacing sticks to the tulip glass for the rest of the drink. Overall a very nice looking Imperial Stout, but nothing that sets it apart.
S- This beer has a beautiful bouquet of wide ranging smells. It starts with a pungent sweet fruity smell by itself, however as you continue to breathe in you get roasted malt flavors as well as chocolate and a faint bourbon hint near the conclusion. This is a very complex smelling beer and a great anticipation builder for when you taste it.
T- This is a mellow tasting beer (maybe because of the duration spent in my cellar). Actually this beer starts a little bitter tasting but as I let the beer warm up it settled down quite nicely. I am picking up a heavy essence of the roasted malt and chocolate flavors but other flavors I smelled are not quite as strong in the taste. The high ABV is masked rather well and is a very nice sipping beer. Overall this is a very good tasting beer (once it settles down and warms up) and is a very good representation of an Imperial Stout.
I have been saving this bottle for a year and a half and am glad that I waited this long to try it out. This beer has definately lived up to the hype and this is one the best tasting/overall presentation beers that I have had the opportunity to drink. I have several 09's sitting and I am convinced that the longer I wait to open the better tasting they will be. This is the epitomy of a beer that gets better with age and I can now see/taste why this beer is so highly rated. 1,650 characterscbros, Jul 14, 2010
4.09/5  rDev -8.7%look: 4.5 | smell: 3 | taste: 4.5 | feel: 5 |  overall: 4Vintage 2009. Poured into an 0.25 liter goblet at Whole Foods in Tustin.
A: Opaque black with almost no light transmission around the edges. Light brown foam head diminishes to a patchy layer. Heavy lacing remains near the top of the glass.
S: Faintly nutty, with no alcohol detectable. Overall very mild, not really noteworthy.
T: Very sweet malt initially with surprising coffee/chocolate bitterness quickly following. The two elements blend together to give the impression of sipping liquid bittersweet chocolate. Aromatic coffee flavors linger in the finish along with a trace of alcohol.
M: Thick, syrupy viscosity with light carbonation--exactly as a beer of this style should be.
D: While this beer is best enjoyed in smaller servings because of its rich flavors and high alcohol content, it is a pleasure to drink. Among other beers of this style, The Abyss really stands out as an example of restraint, balance, and sheer deliciousness. While this is a big beer, it is not trying to be extreme as many other imperial stouts seem. This beer begs to be sipped alongside the most decadent of chocolate desserts. 1,122 charactersbeagle75, Jul 13, 2010
4.46/5  rDev -0.4%look: 5 | smell: 4 | taste: 4.5 | feel: 5 |  overall: 4.522oz bottle poured into a tulip. 2009 release.
A - Viscous black beer initially crowned with a massive cinnamon-brown head. Thick rings of lace coat the glass as it recedes to about a finger's worth.
S - Chocolate leads the way, with highlights of smoke and sweet caramel. Bourbon is mostly hidden, though the oak aging does present a vanilla aroma.
T - Smooth Dutch cocoa flavor is most prominent and lasts through the long finish. Coffee comes in soon after, as well as molasses and a savory smoke flavor. Sweetness gives way to a more bitter roastiness as the beer warms, though there is a lingering caramel character. As it opens up further, there's some dark fruit - fig, raisin, plum. Hop flavor is muted and earthy, with a relatively low hop bitterness.
M - Dense, chewy, and full.
D - Mellow and enjoyable. This is a delicious stout, but I'd rank it below Kate et al. I'd love the opportunity to try this a bit younger, too. 937 characterstrbergman, Jul 11, 2010
