4.7/5  rDev +4.9%look: 4.5 | smell: 4.5 | taste: 5 | feel: 4.5 |  overall: 4.52009 vintage reviewed 07-09-2010. Snifter.
A: Pours a deep dark brown, almost black, with a thick dark mocha colored head that quickly reduced into a bubbly film that left spots of soapy lacing around the glass.
S: Notes of sweet dark fruits, dark malt, molasses, dark cherries, vanilla, and faint bourbon, wood (oak) and alcohol. 
T: Tastes like a smooth mocha. Big notes of dark chocolate and roasted coffee intermittent with a touch of grassy hops. Molasses is present in the finish, and dark chocolate dominates the aftertaste with a hint of licorice. Slight alcohol presence in the finish along with some sweet fruitiness. 
M: Full bodied and divinely smooth. Alcohol is never hot or burning. Soft carbonation is creamy and smooth. Bitterness is low.
D: No infection here. I hope my other bottles are as good as this one so I can enjoy them after the best after date and beyond. This is definitely one of my favorite Deschutes beers. I can't wait for next years.
2007 vintage reviewed 12-18-2010. AVBC snifter.
A: Pours as black as the abyss with a thin dark brown head that quickly faded into a wispy film. 
S: Almost all of the alcohol vapor has been aged away from this one. What is left is a delicious combination of sweet molasses, dark chocolate, roasted grain, and just a hint of coffee.
T: Not as much coffee as my review of the 09 vintage suggests. This beer has aged into one hell of a smooth and subtly flavored stout. This isn't as sweet as the 09 was, or as fruity. I do get more notes of licorice in this one though, especially in the finish. Aftertaste has a dark chocolate bitterness and almost no acidity. 
M: Full bodied and just so damn smooth and creamy. Carbonation is tingly yet soft, and mouthfeel is velvety smooth. The alcohol is masked extremely with no warmth in the finish. 
D: Probably my favorite imperial stout, and not just this vintage, all of them. This is just a phenomenal beer.
2010 vintage reviewed 11-29-2011. Tulip.
A: Pours as black as the other vintages with a huge dark woody head with rusty highlights. A very impressive sheet of sticky lacing was left down the glass.
S: Rich scents of bitter chocolate, oak, molasses, and caramel. Sweet smelling. 
T: Big notes of oak and licorice. Chocolate and molasses come through very strong, and I’m not getting as much coffee as last year. The finish is full of vanilla, and the aftertaste has hints of dark fruits and raisins. The alcohol isn’t hot, but there is a good dose of warmth in the finish. The aftertaste is a little rough around the edges, and definitely more bitter than I remember. Still very good all-around. 
M: Super thick body like always, fluffy carbonation that creates a chewy and viscous body. Decadent as always.
O: Still one of my favorite stouts despite trying many others since the last time I had this beer. I think this year’s still has a little bit more aging to do before it is just perfect.
