4.55/5  rDev +1.6%look: 5 | smell: 5 | taste: 4.5 | feel: 4.5 |  overall: 4Poured from a 22 oz., 2009 reserve bomber into a Dogfish Head signature glass. I may be doing this beer a huge disservice by drinking it so long before its drink-after date, but I'm a huge proponent of being able to drink beers at any time, so here it goes. 
Appearance: As it pours, the beer doesn't look terribly black; rather it's a darker cola color. Once the glass is filled, it becomes an ominous, abyssal black that sucks in all the light around it. The beer is crowned by an equally dark and impressively thick head, that takes an eternity to dissipate. Appearance-wise, this is the quintessential imperial stout. Additionally, there is a pretty high amount of lacing on the glass for a powerful stout. 
Smell: The Abyss has an unbelievably deep and complex nose to it. There is a huge, syrupy and thick smell of fudge brownie malt that is probably most prominent scent. There is some chocolate to found somewhere in the background, as well as some vanilla, which I suspect is a product of the oak aging. There's also a creamy, milky sweet smell in there somewhere, and just a tinge of alcohol. 
Taste: The first sip tells me this is going to be a great beer. Despite being very young, the beer is exceptionally smooth and well-refined. Th first tastes to greet your palate are some imperious fudge malts and a fair degree of roasted malt. The oak (and hence vanilla) is very present in the taste just in case you forgot this was barrel aged. 
The hops are probably the most impressively incorporated taste, in my opinion. There is just the correct amount of resinous, piney hops to counter the immense sweetness of the malts and oak. The hops don't go overboard, though, and leave no cloying on your palate like some lesser stouts have the tendency to do. I'm not sure, however, if I'm willing to give this beer the ultimate score, as the taste is not supremely bold. 
Mouthfeel: The Abyss is an appropriately thick but not a chewy example of the style. The mouthfeel makes up for this lack of body by being astoundingly silky and smooth, however. It is also just about as crisp as an imperial stout is going to be. 
Drinkability: This is a nice-drinking stout but I'm definitely taking my time in getting through this bomber. As it warms, the alcohol starts to make its presence known, but not necessarily through direct taste. Rather, the alcohol provides a nice warming sensation as time goes on. Despite this, the beer is exceptionally smooth and each sip is a pleasure that goes down easily. 
Overall, this is definitely a top-tier beer. It's extraordinarily smooth but it's smoothness is not matched in boldness, which prevents this beer from achieving the ultimate taste score. That being said, this is definitely a phenomenal beer that is masterfully put together. As I mentioned earlier, I'm sure this beer could do with some time in the cellar, but as it is, this is a great beer. 2,906 characterszoso493, Mar 26, 2010
