4.4/5  rDev -1.8%look: 4.5 | smell: 4.5 | taste: 4.5 | feel: 4.5 |  overall: 4First you need someone to share it with. Then you need a tool to get the wax off. I prefer a Dremel tool with a 1/8" router bit. Then you can enjoy...
Aroma:
The dominant aromas of slightly burnt coffee, chocolate, and alcohol stick around but with each sniff new aromas emerge. Bourbon, molasses, licorice, prunes, keep searching...
Appearance:
Pours midnight black. Even when there's just a bit left in the glass you can't see through it. For a high ABV beer the Abyss pours a good sized head which is creamy and sorority girl tan in color. A resilient cap of foam about 1/4" thick protects the beer below all the way until the last few sips. Good clingy lacing. 
Taste:
Many of the aromas you smelled initially come alive on your palate. The velvety smooth heavy bodied beer entices you with chocolate, coffee, bourbon, prunes, molasses, indefinable malty sweetness and of course alcohol. The finish comes around to rescue you from the sweetness with bitter roasted coffee notes that linger long enough to be appreciated but not long enough to annoy. 1,056 charactersbirdypowder, Jan 25, 2010
4.97/5  rDev +10.9%look: 4.5 | smell: 5 | taste: 5 | feel: 5 |  overall: 5A big thanks goes out to redbrewer83 for trusting me in one of my first trades and sending this one out. 2008 reserve.
Poured into the snifters that I bought just for the occasion of tasting this beer with the proper glassware.
A: After hacking the wax off the top of the bottle and opening up the bottle, I grab the glasses. The pour comes thick and viscous that produces head only after the pour. The head is dark, thick, and creamy. The head dissipates very quickly, though not surprisingly at 11% ABV. Lacing is stringy and inconsistent, sliding back into the beer after some time. This is a welcome development, because it gives me a couple more drops of beer to drink.
S: Roasted tobacco goodness streams from the glass. I can make out an amazing oakey vanilla aromas as well. There is some muted caramel that linger in the wings with a bittersweet chocolate fragrance. There is a touch of alcohol as well, but it is not an astringent character in this beer.
T: WOW. This beer has an amazing level of complexity and balance. Nothing overwhelms or overshadows any other flavors in the beer. Initally, there is a nice taste of roasted tobacco, which is balanced beautifully with some coffee. The flavor then reveals a surprisingly well-developed oakey vanilla that works nicely with caramel notes that are extremely formidable for a component that didn't show up in the nose at all. Bourbon then comes through, adding a great layer to this beer, again, not stealing the show, which is usually a critical flaw of bourbon-aged beers. Chocolate is almost last among all of the other flavors, but it can come through in the middle if you really look for it. Aftertaste is oakey vanilla, tobacco, and coffee.
M/D: Creamy, smooth, viscous, and absolutely sublime. It slides over the palate and down the back with a nice dry finish. This is without a doubt the best RIS that I have ever had, though it may be more American Imperial Stout...This is deep, complex, balanced, and no single flavor becomes the focal point of this beer. I will definitely be trading for more of these as soon as the opportunity presents itself. 2,124 charactersNittanyBeerFan, Jan 24, 2010
4.9/5  rDev +9.4%look: 5 | smell: 5 | taste: 5 | feel: 5 |  overall: 4.52009 reserve, from a wax sealed 22 oz bomber into a oversized wine glass into my belly.
A- Killer head on this bad boy- thick, fluffy, dirty brown head atop a molten puddle of primal tar. The great head mellows out to a quarter finger thick top. My god is this dark. Nice.
S- Whoa, spicy alcohol and hops are dominating the nose, but more deep inhales reveal chocolate covered rose petals, sugared pipe tobacco, strong perfumey notes, aged port, cheap coffee and holy christ I think I even smell hints of mint in here. 
This smell is beyond words-- so good and so complex and so damn deep. This is what Heaven's brewery smells like. I can't stop putting my entire face in the glass for another giant whiff.
T- Here we go...
The Abyss has a sprawling, evolving taste. First is sugar cookie- like sweet malts, than moving into Deschutes' perfectly balanced stout as the turning point, eventually flowing into a mild alcohol and bitter hops burn. Wonderful movement of flavors, and with such a perfect mouthfeel. The alcohol is quite present, however, more so than the BCS I reviewed days ago at a higher 13% ABV. I suspect the strong flavor of hops helps the warmth of this relatively strong stout. But I have to confess I am in awe of the sheer number of flavors and the way it transforms into something totally different at the end than what your first tasted. World class beer craftsmanship, ya'll. Your expertise is evident, and appreciated! 
Perfect 5 for taste, too.
M- Surprisingly a thinner body than I expected, but it seems to aid in the more delicate sweet flavors of the beer. Excellent structure and feel- very smooth texture with almost no carbonation for maximum silkiness. Yes, quite excellent.
D- Yet another fantastic imperial stout to lust after all year. The only fault I can find is in it's just-less-than-ideal drinkability-- the finish is quite intense and lingering, coats the tongue and mouth with sticky bitterness. 1,947 charactersSamN, Jan 23, 2010
