4.4/5  rDev -1.8%look: 4.5 | smell: 4.5 | taste: 4.5 | feel: 4.5 |  overall: 42010 Vintage
A: Pours a deep black with a nice big dark brown head that fades to a ring and leaves some nice lacing on the glass.
S: The nose is dominated by coffee and roasted malt aromas. Smells like a coffee stout with not much else in there.
T: The taste is dark chocolate and roasted/burnt malt with subtle vanilla and molasses flavors on the finish. The sweet flavors balance out the dark roasty flavors pretty well.
M: The feel is medium bodied but kind of thin. Not the thickest stout but it's creamy and coats the mouth.
D: Pretty tasty but the aromas and mouthfeel seem a bit on the low end this year. I still plan to drink another after a year of age....hopefully it doesn't sour like the 2009 version.
***
2009 vintage 22oz bomber poured into a Brooklyn snifter.
A: Pours an inky black with a big creamy dark tan head that fades to a nice layering across the top and leaves excellent lacing on the side of the glass. Head retention was very nice.
S: The nose is complex with aromas of chocolate/cocoa, earth/tobacco, molassess, malt/grain, some dark fruits in the background, and very faint hops.
T: First tastes are dark chocolate/cocoa, vanilla, and a big roasty/hop bitterness. After a few sips the bitterness isn't that noticeable and more flavors come to the front. Dark fruit and molassess are evident as the beer warms.
M: The feel is thick yet not too thick and pretty creamy. Good carbonation.
D: I would probably only want one bomber in a sitting but I can't wait to see how this ages and plan to have it again in a year or so. I would definitely drink this all the time if I had access to more.
I was expecting slightly more out of this one but it was still very complex and tasty. The barrel aging isn't as noticeable as I thought it would be but it is a blend. The vanilla and dark fruit flavors really come out after this warms along with other flavors so let it sit a while. Definitely a sipper. 1,935 charactersGregSVT, Jan 20, 2010
