4.92/5  rDev +9.8%look: 4.5 | smell: 5 | taste: 5 | feel: 4.5 |  overall: 52008 vintage. Poured into a tulip glass. Thanks to Rhinos00 for splitting this.
A- Black as the Abyss with next to no highlights. Pours with a frothy coffee ice cream colored head with a great mix of bubble sizes. The head recedes quickly but retains many of its bubbles. The head throws huge streams of lacing up the sides of the glass right away and does so throughout the drink.
S- Licorice, alcohol, roasted coffee beans, roasted barley and a subdued bourbon all play along in perfect harmony. There is a bitterness from the roast as well as an dark chocolate, ovaltine-like maltiness that lets me know I'm going to love this.
T- Malt balls, lactose milkiness, dark fruit and licorice, bourbon and roasted barley. These flavors all lead your mouth on a 30 second roller coaster ride, ending with a huge drop off into an intense roasted barley and roasted coffee bean aftertaste. Great complexity that makes me wait out the entire experience before I take my next sip.
M- Not as viscous as I was expecting. Medium bodied for a bigger stout with low to medium carbonation. 
D- So drinkable for such a high alcohol stout. Minimal alcohol burn, which I didn't even describe above, allows this to be consumed much quicker than a sipper. The mouthfeel invites bigger mouthfuls than is probably recommended. One of my most memorable stouts ever. Can't wait to try the other vintages. 1,385 charactersPecorasc, Jan 16, 2010
