4.45/5  rDev -0.7%look: 4.5 | smell: 4.5 | taste: 4.5 | feel: 4 |  overall: 4.5I've had this on tap and out of the bottle now, just really wanted to hone this in before reviewing it. Sometimes, the greatest beers need to be had a few times to make sure hype / expectations aren't skewing the palate at all, and such was the case with Abyss.
09 Vintage, 07 and 08 in the cellar, so this review may be changed later.
Appearance: Very dark amber brown black, and looks like a murky swamp with some dirty edges. Laces nicely as well, but a little low out of the bottle. 
Smell: Molasses-y sweetness, caramel, a little rum-raisin, slight brown sugar, prune, chocolate, anise, and vanilla-oaky character. Booze is mildly present, but limited to more of an attribute than a dominant character.
Taste: Molasses and chocolate up-front with a coffee-like roast and a bit of spiciness from some still-fresh hops. A little sweet yet, and a little alcoholic warmth in the finish, but altogether very, very pleasant. The tap was much more molasses driven in character but less sweet than out of the bottle; I bet a year to three would do absolute wonders.
Mouthfeel: Only real hiccup for me here, as it was carbonated appropriately but not as thick as I'd hoped for out of an 11% beer. Don't get me wrong, it's still excellent, but with this sweetness I hoped for a bit thicker and creamier texture than what was given.
Drinkability: Drinks under the ABV and is smooth, tasty, and full of complexity and flavor. On tap may have been a little too carbonated, but the flavors were more intense. Definitely a great big stout, and love the increased bottle numbers this year allowing me to pick up almost a case to age, as I have a feeling this is only going to get better as the residual sugars ferment out and add a whole 'nother dimension to this already very tasty brew. 1,783 charactersnomomentwasted, Dec 14, 2009
