A - Poured a deep, dark brown - bordering black - body with a slim burnt tan head that diminished and left a bit of spotty lacing around the glass.
S - Initial whiff reveals an odd, yet intoxicating blend of chocolate milkshake and beef jerky. Hmmmm... interesting, to say the least. Oak and woody notes also emerge, followed by a touch of alcohol and a subtle earthy hop character. 
T - This RIS opens with the flavor of sweet milk chocolate paired with a mild meaty, beef jerky character. Suggestions of molasses and licorice emerge in the middle and mingle with more earthy, woody notes and some dark roasted maltiness. Finishes with an earthy hop bitterness. 
M - Medium bodied with a silky, smooth texture and soft carbonation. No noticeable alcohol presence for such a huge RIS! Finishes with a moderate earthy bitterness on the palate.
D - Wow! This is an impressive RIS for sure. This drinks like a champ for such a hefty alcohol presence. At 11% ABV, this is about as drinkable as you can get for a RIS, especially one that is as complex as this. 1,130 charactersffejherb, Jan 11, 2009
4.8/5  rDev +7.1%look: 5 | smell: 5 | taste: 5 | feel: 5 |  overall: 4Well well well. My review for probably the best beer I have ever consumed. 
The appearance is that of syrup. Pours incredibly dark, and when it pours the aroma just explodes into the air rushing your senses like a herd of bulls. I poured the head to three fingers height just to get the oxygen flowing and the aroma all over the room. The head is a caramel color that, for me, came down to about a finger height. You can hold a spotlight up to this beer and nothing will penetrate through. 
Like I said previously the smell is so smeet and intoxifying that you just want to bathe in the brew. I can smell black licorice, caramel, and the alcohol. I just want to breath it all day long, I want the smell to be in my nose forever. 
The taste is so complex that I might not even be able to describe the taste. Its like sucking off the tit of the Virgin Mary, how about that? It dances on the tongue, telling your body that you are unworthy of this nector from the God's. Sometimes I can taste the licorice and its the most overwhelming characteristic of the beer, and sometimes it is the caramel and chocolate flavors with an alcohol aftertaste. Every time it is so different. Every time I fell bad that I am drinking it because I feel like it might be the cure to cancer. 
The mouthfeel is really enjoyable because the beer does this really nice dance on your palate before foaming up into this great chocolate alcoholic taste that just washes down so sweetly that you want to just weep. I love this beer for the fact that it just tastes like the best Russian Imperial Stout that has ever existed. 
The first time I had this was back in the beginning of the holiday season and I just remember having this smile plastered to my face. You drink one and its so filling and satisfying that you want another. I had two the first time I had it and it was just a little too much of a good thing. I was overwhelmed. 
Whenever, if ever again, I see this beer in the store I will sell my car to get more of these. Currently sitting with ten but I do know of a place that has more. At twelve dollars a bottle it is an expensive drink but oh oh so worth it. 
