4.62/5  rDev +3.1%look: 4.5 | smell: 5 | taste: 4.5 | feel: 4.5 |  overall: 4.5***UPDATE 06/21/2010***
Reviewing an '07 vintage of this one today, which I got off LiquidSolutions before it went out of business. It's been sitting in my cellar for a year and change now, and I suppose has to be 2.5 years old at this point. And it's drinking beautifully. Drinkability gets half a point bump for being so damn inviting. Unsure how much better it will get, or even - now that I'm contemplating it further - if it may have peaked very recently. Either way, I wouldn't object to anyone with an '07 cracking it now.
***
Enjoyed at a tasting on 06/18 w/ fellow BAer proteus93. This beer was actually courteous of proteus - thanks!! Poured into an Ommegang chalice.
Appearance: An abyss, fittingly. Black as night with a deep, brown head that is huge, creamy, permanent. No light escapes through this one (we checked with my laser pointer, just to be sure). Retention is actually great for a 11% abv beer, as is the lacing. Stellar.
Aroma: Probably the most complex smelling beer I've ever stuck my nose into. A number of woody notes are definitely present - an earthy oak note, vanilla phenols, and some wood toastiness are all present up front. But that's just the beginning - highly toasted but not burnt malts lend the impression of coffee, toffee, and bitter chocolate. Soy sauce, salt, wholesome oats, licorice, some fruity esters, and light, wafting alcohol are also all pleasant. Simply outstanding.
Taste: Much of what's in the nose, and that's a good thing. Highly roasted malts come through as baker's chocolate, highly roasted coffee, and molasses. Dark, complex fruity sugars come through at the apex of the sip - figs, prunes, raisins. The anise is there, but it's not distracting or dominating, which is good, as its not my favorite flavor. Despite all this complex sweetness, however, it's well-balanced with a strong but understated spicy hop presence, stronger than many RISs. There's alcohol, too, obviously, but it's smooth and warming, not coarse and hot.
Mouthfeel: Full and creamy, luscious and smooth, but with a surprisingly solid carbonation base. Strangely enough, I have no notes on the bubble profile. Does this mean it was too good for words? Or so bad I was speechless? Or that this was the 6th beer of the evening, five of them over 9% abv, and I was too gone to even properly say the words "bubble structure," much less write cogently about it? I think it's probably the last one there.
Drinkability: Eminently drinkable, but at 11% abv it's obviously a sipper, and a beer to respect. Not overwhelmingly sweet, either, like many other RISs - this one would go well on its own or with a savory dessert.
What an outstanding beer. A new top-10er for me. A delicate yet bold, complex but defined beer, and definitely one to be savored. If you see it, buy every last one. 2,820 charactersCrellMoset, Jun 29, 2008
4.28/5  rDev -4.5%look: 4.5 | smell: 4 | taste: 4.5 | feel: 4.5 |  overall: 4Had this as my first beer of the night on tap at Uber Tavern in Seattle.
