4.25/5  rDev -5.1%look: 4 | smell: 4 | taste: 4.5 | feel: 4.5 |  overall: 4Abyss from a 2007 bottle and poured into a Brandy Snifter.
A - dark black with a thin mocha colored head that barely sits on the edge. The beer has a dark reflective sheen to it as well. There was hardly any head at all and not a trace of lacing to be found as well. There was a thick and sticky aspect of the beer that let the beer coat the sides of the glass but that only stayed on for a few seconds as well.
S - Smells of a deep burnt and smoky malt that wafts up. I was really surprised by how smoky and roasted the nose was. Had that almost beef jerky like smell that dominates some beers of the style. There were also loads of thick dark chocolate that came to me as the beer warmed up even more from cellar to room temp. The smoky aspect really seemed to dominate the nose of the beer and that seemed to take away from the subtle aspects that were trying to make themselves noticed. There was a light hint of caramel, vanilla, oak and even black berries that seemed to come out a bit more as the beer reached high temps.
T - At first, there was a sweet chocolate malt that rolled over the tongue with a hint of vanilla sweetness. It managed to be sweet without being overly sweet. There were hints of plum, blueberry, and anise as well that gave the beer a sharp bite and snap to it. I could definitely get a some of the oak spices as well as I noted a hint of cinnamon. At a 11%, I also every once and awhile got a taste of the alcohol which just gave the beer a bit more of a snap. in there aftertaste and finish, there was a hint of a light roasted coffee flavor. It was a complex beer that had a lot going on and definitely much more subtle and refined than the nose.
MF - The body was probably my favorite aspect of this beer. It managed to have a nice medium body with a light hint of stickiness that just helps it to coat the tongue. I also in the after feeling had a nice light astringent tingle that sat on the tongue as the oak spices faded away.
D - Overall this was a good RIS but definitely not one of the top beers that I've ever had. The smoke dominated nose really could have been improved and been more complex. Despite the nose, the taste was complex and full of flavor and the mouthfeel was great as well. This was a beer that the more I had of it, the more it grew on me. However, I was a little let down with this being a top 10 beer. 2,368 charactersjeonseh, May 28, 2008
4.47/5  rDev -0.2%look: 4 | smell: 4.5 | taste: 4.5 | feel: 4.5 |  overall: 4.5Thanks to blisscent for sharing this one. Served in a standard pint glass. Poured an opaque black with a mocha-colored head. Scents of chocolate, coffee, brewer's licorice and malt hit you in the face. Taste is consistent with nose, with the addition of vanilla and a subdued, balanced oakiness; just enough to enhance the flavors without dominating. Finish has a light hoppy character. Mouthfeel was silky without being viscous, and alcohol was well-hidden. The Abyss is by far one of the most drinkable RIS's I've had the opportunity to try. It goes down deceptively smooth and leaves you wanting for more. I plan on opening the bottle I was able to procure (thanks msubulldog25) sometime in the late Fall/early Winter and I am anxiously anticipating how this brew is going to continue to develop. 799 charactersJwale73, May 26, 2008
