4.66/5  rDev +4%look: 5 | smell: 4 | taste: 5 | feel: 5 |  overall: 4.5Talk about dumb luck, I managed to find both this and Pliny the Younger on tap at Toronado while in San Francisco. I also found a few bottles of this but the review is from Toronado, served in a tulip.
A: Dense pitch black. Deep mocha, coffee colored head that dissipates to a thin film and lines the glass. Basically perfect looking for a RIS, only complaint might be wishing for a slightly thicker head, but I'm going to ignore that as part of the pour.
S: Ok, sometimes in bars I have trouble picking up a good nose on a beer and I'm afraid this is one of those cases. A little sweetness from licorice and some raisin but primarily roasted flavors (chocolate, coffee, etc). Definite bourbon/alcohol pinch.
T: Yea, I'm usually skeptical of beers with this much hype and well, this delivered. I like RISs but am sometimes turned off by the bitterness of them. This was much less bitter than say Old Rasputin. Incredibly smoothed and well balanced, tons of roast malt, chocolate, coffee, oak flavors all in balance. Finish is slightly more sweet and roasted than the body and I would expect some people to look for more a hop/bitter taste, but I'm perfectly happy with the taste. It's very complex and enjoyable and had to go back for a second pour. Obviously at 11% abv there is a slight taste of alcohol hiding in the background, but nothing unpleasant or overpowering.
M: So thick, creamy, smooth, rich....Light carbonation, just, perfect....
D: For such a powerful, complex beer this is very easy to drink, nothing is too out of control but I just notch this down from a 5 since while I loved this, I certainly still need to be in the mood to drink this. I also definitely preferred the draft version over the bottle. Flavors just seemed more balanced and smooth and would probably let the bottles sit a little before drinking them again. 1,843 charactersyourefragile, Feb 06, 2008
