4.5/5  rDev +0.4%look: 4.5 | smell: 4.5 | taste: 4.5 | feel: 4.5 |  overall: 4.5Even though I grabbed a bottle of this my first experience was on tap at the new Liar's Club Alpine. 10 oz pour into a tulip glass.
Poured jet black with a very large brown head that stuck around for awhile. A gentle swirl would pillow the head back up at least a half inch as the beer warmed.
Aromas were exactly what I expected. Chocolate, molasses, oak, vanilla, roasted barley, very subtle licorice.
Taste was extremely complex. While 33% of this is barrel aged and then blended back in those are really the background flavors. None of that hot bourbon character some barrel aged stouts take on. Chocolate and roasted grains with some vanilla from the oak. Definitely some espresso flavors present.
Mouthfeel is a creamy delight. Very full bodied and with the perfect amount of carbonation, this just slides down easily and you hardly notice its high ABV.
I give it a high drinkability when being compared the other beers in it's category. I could probably get through a 22oz bottle by myself easily, but no more than that.
Some may call this overrated just because of all the hype it receives before it's released but I would say it's worthy and stands tall among the other RIS examples. I'll look forward to this seasonal every year. 1,245 characterskleffman, Jan 28, 2008
