4.37/5  rDev -2.5%look: 4.5 | smell: 5 | taste: 4.5 | feel: 4 |  overall: 3.5Got this bottle in trade from Alaska. Thankee Edgelow.
I didn't expect a beer called "Abyss" to be anything other than deepest black, and that's pretty much what this is. In my glass it looks like ink topped with a rapidly fading cinnamon-brown head. Pretty.
Ahh, now we get to it! The Abyss has a heckuva nose. Rich chocolate cake, cocoa powder, oak-wood, espresso, and a sweet roastedness pervades everything. I'm also picking up a dirty, earthy smell and molasses, finished off by considerable alcohol heat. Yummy.
The flavor is primarily deep coffee and cocoa, tastes "organic" if that makes any sense. Pure, I suppose. Molasses and rich, lingering bittersweet cocoa in the finish. The alcohol is cunningly hid behind the coffee-cocoa assault, but you know it's there. The mouthfeel is slick, lowly carbonated, sticky and chewy. Finishes dry and with the same experience you get if you chew a handful of coffee beans. Nice. I'm not tasting much oak character, though.
Drinkable? It's a fine sipping beer, yes. Much like it's older, eviler cousin Dark Lord; I don't require more than 6 ounces of this at a time. Take a while to drink and study this one. Best savored inside a log cabin fireplace in Oregon while Old Man Winter howls outside, angry that he can't share in your coffee-booze delight that is Abyss.
Ultimately, the Abyss didn't grab me like it apparently does everyone else. It's merely Very Good. Still, gets my unqualified recommendation as one of the better Russian Imperial Stouts out there. 1,516 characterskkipple, Sep 18, 2007
4.58/5  rDev +2.2%look: 5 | smell: 4.5 | taste: 4.5 | feel: 5 |  overall: 4.5Incredibly lucky to find that they had this available in the beer tasting room at the LA County fair (didn't last long I don't think - got a glass at about 7PM, was no longer there at 8:30). 12oz pour for $5 - I'd say that's the best deal I've ever seen at a fair!
Pours a ridiculously black black with a 1/2 finger dark tan head that does stay around nicely. This beer just looks beautiful.
Smell is of tons of chocolate and roasted flavors. Loving it.
Taste is delicious. Dark chocolate. Milk chocolate. Coffee. More chocolate. Touch of nice hop bitterness to perfectly balance the sweets. Oh man, this thing is dessert in a glass. The balance here is truly exceptional. This is how I like my stouts.
Mouthfeel is so rich yet so smooth, lending an amazing drinkability to such a potent beer. The alcohol is only really tasted in a nice bourbon warmth sort of way - nice.
Wonderful, wonderful beer. Deschutes knows how to brew (and oak age). Highly recommended. Shall revisit soon hopefully! 997 charactersrallison, Sep 13, 2007
4.73/5  rDev +5.6%look: 5 | smell: 4.5 | taste: 5 | feel: 4.5 |  overall: 4.5One pint 6 fluid oz.s (of black deliciousness), 2006 reserve, aged in French oak and bourbon barrels. The bottle black, a black wax seal, the label an earthy brown with a crack (the abyss, apparently) down the middle. Visual translation: not f'ing around.
To begin with, a foreshadowing if you will, one must chip away at the black wax seal to even get a proper grip to remove the cap. Pouring into a tulip glass, black as oil even when held to a light, the two finger head a dark tan, frothy, bubbly, long lasting. The lacing is left all around the glass, in small splotches, long streaks, rambling amoebas, as though leaving behind traces of destruction, its perfect.
The aroma is all kind of dark, roasted goodness. Smoky, roasted malts are used wantonly, chocolates abound, bourbon soaked cherries and figs and charred coffee grounds stinging the nose, and I like it. 
The taste defines the phrase, 'instant classic.' Its a mean one, serious, gripping... again, not f'ing around. A complex, intricate, evolving beast of palatable proportions. Roasted malts are in huge abundance, black as midnight malts, slightly oaky, the bourbon influence no fleeting thing yet only in flavor, not biting or bracing, only its warmth. Pounds of bittersweet chocolate, vanilla, molasses and dark fruits swirl around, tumbling into oblivion (or maybe thats my sobriety...).
The mouth is full, smooth, slightly chewy even, carbonated to the slightest degree, hardly noticeable but ever effective, the alcohol presence very much present and warming. The finish is long and drawn out, leaving me to consider what I'll have to do to acquire a bottle of next year's batch. And I must say, though I have no base of reflection, it has in fact (and coinciding with rumor) peaked, so, as my best bud would say, "Drrrink up, fuckers!!"
Of the fantastic uber-stouts I've had recently, Surly Darkness easily rank as my favorite, AleSmith Speedway Stout an honorable second, and this third. I chose this one as I pass onto 450th review, 800th karma point, and to celebrate a month till my wedding. Hopefully, I'll have a Dark Lord to celebrate next month... the Abyss, and Dark Lord, how appropriate. :)
Thanks go to RoBotGod for this one. 2,219 charactersobjectivemonkey, Sep 09, 2007
